# Hypothesis — Alpha Engine

*Written before building. Updated as evidence accumulates.*

---

## Core Claim

Alternative data signals from job postings, skill hiring patterns, and 
retail search interest can predict which Indian IT stocks will outperform 
the Nifty IT index over the following 7–30 days — before that information 
appears in earnings reports or analyst coverage.

---

## Signal 1 — Job Posting Velocity (Naukri.com)

**Hypothesis:**
When an Indian IT company posts jobs at a rate significantly above its own 
12-week baseline, it is likely responding to new contract wins or expansion 
of existing engagements. This revenue activity will show up in quarterly 
earnings 1–2 quarters later, but the stock should begin repricing within 
3–6 weeks of the hiring signal.

**Direction:** Positive — more hiring above baseline → expect outperformance

**Why it might work:**
- IT services companies hire specifically for projects, not speculatively
- Hiring leads revenue recognition by 6–12 weeks
- Naukri data is public but not systematically monitored by institutional investors
- Indian retail investors don't use this data at all

**Why it might not work:**
- Companies post ghost jobs to build a talent pipeline, not for specific contracts
- Large caps (TCS, Infosys) hire continuously — signal is noisier
- Naukri doesn't capture LinkedIn, referrals, or campus hiring
- Short history means z-scores are based on small baselines

---

## Signal 2 — Skill Mix and Velocity

**Hypothesis:**
The *type* of hiring matters more than the *quantity*. A sudden spike in 
cloud or AI hiring signals a strategic pivot or new high-margin contract. 
A company increasing legacy (SAP, mainframe) hiring is filling existing 
low-margin work, not winning new business.

**Sub-hypotheses:**

| Skill category | Expected direction | Logic |
|---|---|---|
| Cloud velocity | Positive | Cloud contracts are high-margin, growing |
| AI/ML velocity | Negative ⚠️ | Rapid AI hiring = cost pressure, not revenue |
| Digital share | Positive | Digital transformation = premium pricing |
| Legacy share | Negative | Maintenance work = margin compression |

**Key finding so far:**
AI/ML hiring velocity turned out to be a negative signal (IC = -0.37). 
This is the "bad news hiring" effect — companies suddenly hiring many AI 
engineers are signalling they are behind competitors and scrambling to 
catch up. Short-term: more cost, uncertain revenue. This is counterintuitive 
but makes economic sense and is worth investigating further.

---

## Signal 3 — Google Search Interest (India)

**Hypothesis:**
Retail investors in India Google a stock before buying it. A spike in 
search interest above a company's own baseline predicts retail buying 
pressure over the following 1–2 weeks, which shows up as price outperformance.

**Direction:** Positive — search spike → expect outperformance

**Why it might work:**
- Indian retail participation has grown enormously since 2020
- Search precedes action — people research before they trade
- Google Trends is free and rarely used as a systematic signal in India

**Why it might not work:**
- Search spikes can be caused by bad news (scandal, layoffs) not just buying intent
- Monthly granularity in long date ranges limits precision
- Signal may be very short-lived (1–3 days) — weekly data may be too slow

---

## Prediction (Testable)

A combined signal from all three sources, when significantly positive 
(z-score > 1.0 on at least two signals), predicts the stock will outperform 
the Nifty IT index by >1% over the following 7 days.

**Universe:** 20 Nifty IT stocks (see README for full list)

**Target metric:** 7-day forward excess return vs Nifty IT index

**Success criteria:**
- Mean IC > 0.05 on at least 2 features (after 20+ weeks)
- Walk-forward Sharpe > 0.5 after transaction costs
- Permutation test p-value < 0.10 on hit rate metric

